\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\g}_{v}(0)=v$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\shape italic
Jacobi field
\shape default
 
\begin_inset Formula $J(t)$
\end_inset

 along a geodesic 
\begin_inset Formula $\g$
\end_inset

 is a vector field along 
\begin_inset Formula $\g$
\end_inset

 which satisfies the following Jacobi equation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J''(t)+K(\g(t))\dot{\g}(t)=0
\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is the Gaussian curvature and 
\begin_inset Formula $'$
\end_inset

 denotes the covariant derivative along 
\begin_inset Formula $\g$
\end_inset

.
 A Jacobi field is called 
\shape italic
orthogonal
\shape default
 if both 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $J'$
\end_inset

 are orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\g}$
\end_inset

 at some 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{0}\in\R$
\end_inset

 (and hence for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\R)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout --Separator--

\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
A Riemannian surface 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 has 
\shape italic
no focal points
\shape default
 if for any initial vanishing orthogonal Jacobi field 
\begin_inset Formula $J(t)$
\end_inset

, its length 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert J(t)\right\Vert $
\end_inset

 is strictly increasing.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 has
\shape italic
 no conjugate points
\shape default
 if any non-zero Jacobi field has at most one zero.
\end_layout

