\begin_layout Standard
It is a classical result that one can identify the tangent space of 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{1}M$
\end_inset

 with the space of orthogonal Jacobi fields 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal J}$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, one can use this relation to define three 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal F}$
\end_inset

 invariant bundles 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{u},E^{c},$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{s}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $TT^{1}S$
\end_inset

.
 To be more precise, let us denote 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal J}(\g)$
\end_inset

 the space of space of orthogonal Jacobi fields along a geodesics 
\begin_inset Formula $\g$
\end_inset

.
 For any 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in T^{1}M$
\end_inset

, the identification between 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{v}T^{1}M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal J}(\g_{v})$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T_{v}T^{1}M\ni\xi\mapsto J_{\xi}\in{\cal J}(\g_{v})
\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{\xi}$
\end_inset

 is the Jacobi field determined by the initial data 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\Vert df_{t}(\xi)\right\Vert ^{2}=\left\Vert J_{\xi}(t)\right\Vert ^{2}+\left\Vert J'_{\xi}(t)\right\Vert ^{2}.\label{eq:metric_jacobi_unit_tangent_bundle}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


